body:
AFAIK - we already support 4-D tensor in NCHW format resizing where batch > 1 and scale > 1. The only limitation is imposed on **scales** (not the input itself). For such a 4-D input, outermost scales must be both 1 (i.e.) we support "bilinear" resizing (outermost scales requiring to be 1) for multi-channel  multi-batch inputs.

To simplify:

1) Input shape that is currently accepted by ORT:
input_shape = [2, 3, 224, 224] (2 images each with 3 channels)
scales_shape = [1, 1, x, x]

Is this what you need ?

2) Input shape (that is valid per spec) but not yet supported by ORT:
input_shape = [2, 3, 224, 224] (2 images each with 3 channels)
scales_shape = [2, 2, x, x]

This is not supported yet as "quadrilinear" resizing is not supported yet.

Sharing a simple single node model (with just Resize node) and some toy expected inputs/ expected outputs will help.

> AFAIK - we already support 4-D tensor in NCHW format resizing where batch > 1 and scale > 1. The only limitation is imposed on **scales** (not the input itself). For such a 4-D input, outermost scales must be both 1 (i.e.) we support "bilinear" resizing (outermost scales requiring to be 1) for multi-channel multi-batch inputs.

>    scales_shape = [2, 2, x, x]
> 
> This is not supported yet as "quadrilinear" resizing is not supported yet.
> 
> Sharing a simple single node model (with just Resize node) and some toy expected inputs/ expected outputs will help.

The Resize operator was conveted from pytorch `interpolate` operator. So I cannot verify if your suggestion 1 works. What I need is definitely your suggestion 1.

I found the convertion script in pytorch symbolic_opset11.py as this
```
def _interpolate(name, dim, interpolate_mode):
    def symbolic_fn(g, input, output_size, align_corners=None):
        align_corners = sym_help._maybe_get_scalar(align_corners)
        output_size = sym_help._maybe_get_const(output_size, 'is')
        if sym_help._is_value(output_size):
            offsets = g.op("Constant", value_t=torch.ones(2, dtype=torch.int64))
            output_size = g.op("Cast", output_size, to_i=sym_help.cast_pytorch_to_onnx["Long"])
            output_size = g.op("Concat", offsets, output_size, axis_i=0)
        else:
            output_size = [1 if i < 2 else output_size[-(dim - i)] for i in range(0, dim)]
            output_size = g.op("Constant", value_t=torch.tensor(output_size))
        coordinate_transformation_mode = "asymmetric" if interpolate_mode == "nearest" \
            else "align_corners" if align_corners else "pytorch_half_pixel"
        empty_tensor = g.op("Constant", value_t=torch.tensor([], dtype=torch.float32))
        return g.op("Resize",
                    input,
                    empty_tensor,  # roi only takes effect whith coordinate_transformation_mode="tf_crop_and_resize"
                    empty_tensor,  # scales is not needed since we are sending out_size
                    output_size,
                    coordinate_transformation_mode_s=coordinate_transformation_mode,
                    cubic_coeff_a_f=-0.75,  # only valid when mode="cubic"
                    mode_s=interpolate_mode,  # nearest, linear, or cubic
                    nearest_mode_s="floor")  # only valid when mode="nearest"
    return symbolic_fn
```
Here we can notice that `scales` are not given in the conversion. So the question is, why ORT still check the `scales`? and where the `scales` under checkment comes from? I looked into the `scales` and found that it is 4-D, and I have no idea where it comes from.

Please check the ONNX spec for Resize - https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators.md#Resize. It has an input 'scales' that defines the final output shape of the resized tensor.

Any conversion framework (in this case - the PyTorch exporter) if generating an ONNX model, should comply with the ONNX spec and hence the final model will have scales in it, even if you can't see it in the conversion snippet you pasted.  (I think scales is being computed by the given `output_size` and the `input` in `g.op()`). I

If it is case-1 you need, it is supported by ORT. Please share the converted ONNX model you get from PyTorch and the expected input and output and someone will help take a look. Thanks.

Due to slow CPU inference speed of Pytorch on Windows, I decided to switch to doing inference with onnxruntime, which is much faster. However, I also encountered this issue while converting my model. I worked around it by modifying `torch/onnx/symbolic_opset11.py` as follows.

Original code in `_interpolate`:

            empty_tensor = g.op("Constant", value_t=torch.tensor([], dtype=torch.float32))
            return g.op("Resize",
                        input,
                        empty_tensor,  # roi only takes effect whith coordinate_transformation_mode="tf_crop_and_resize"
                        empty_tensor,  # scales is not needed since we are sending out_size
                        output_size,
                        coordinate_transformation_mode_s=coordinate_transformation_mode,
                        cubic_coeff_a_f=-0.75,  # only valid when mode="cubic"
                        mode_s=interpolate_mode,  # nearest, linear, or cubic
                        nearest_mode_s="floor")  # only valid when mode="nearest"

Modified code:

            empty_tensor = g.op("Constant", value_t=torch.tensor([], dtype=torch.float32))
            scales = sym_help._interpolate_size_to_scales(g, input, output_size, dim)
            return g.op("Resize",
                        input,
                        empty_tensor,  # roi only takes effect whith coordinate_transformation_mode="tf_crop_and_resize"
                        scales,
                        coordinate_transformation_mode_s=coordinate_transformation_mode,
                        cubic_coeff_a_f=-0.75,  # only valid when mode="cubic"
                        mode_s=interpolate_mode,  # nearest, linear, or cubic
                        nearest_mode_s="floor")  # only valid when mode="nearest"

However, I believe this is actually a bug in onnxruntime. The ONNX specs say:

> sizes (optional) : tensor(int64)
> The size of the output tensor. The number of elements of 'sizes' should be the same as the rank of input 'X'. **Only one of 'scales' and 'sizes' can be specified.**

This implies that requiring scales or both scales and sizes as onnxruntime does is not correct.

> @yangia I have met the same problem as you described, and I tried to solve it with your trials, in my solution I used torch.split and torch.cat, the solution to traversal the sliced tensor I used is FOR structure.
> Then I got the error: TracerWarning: Converting a tensor to a Python index might cause the trace to be incorrect. We can't record the data flow of Python values, so this value will be treated as a constant in the future. This means that the trace might not generalize to other inputs!
> Have you met this problem and how did you solve it? Thanks so much if you can reply me.

I didn't use torch.split. I silced with `for`, and then concatenated with torch.cat. The conversion of torch.split seems to have something wrong with it. Not sure.

issue.title: pytorch Upsampling with align_corners = True

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
On MacOS, the pytorch Upsample layer:

`torch.nn.Upsample(scale_factor=2,  mode='bilinear',  align_corners = True)`

does not seem to work well with `onnxruntime`, even if properly exported/tested with `torch.onnx` and `onnx`. The option `align_corners = False` seems to be working fine. I have also tried `opset_version=10`.


**Urgency**
It seems to be working on Windows. We are planning to release a Mac version of your software in May 2020 -- this would be fantastic if this could be fixed.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution: MacOS Sierra 10.12.6
- ONNX Runtime version: 0.5.0
- Python version: 3.6.9
- CUDA/cuDNN version: None
- GPU model and memory: None

**To Reproduce**

```python
#create a simple function
import torch
class simple(torch.nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(simple, self).__init__()
        self.up = torch.nn.Upsample(scale_factor=2, 
                                    mode='bilinear', 
                                    align_corners = True)
    def forward(self, x):
        output = self.up(x)
        return output

# sanity check
net = simple()
batch_size, channel, dimx, dimy = 2,3,5,7
batch_input = torch.zeros(batch_size, channel, dimx, dimy).float()
output = net(batch_input)


#export the model
import torch.onnx
torch.onnx.export(net,            # model being run
                  batch_input,    # model input (or a tuple for multiple inputs)
                  "model.onnx",   # where to save the model (can be a file or file-like object)
                  export_params=True,        # store the trained parameter weights inside the model file
                  opset_version=11,          # the ONNX version to export the model to
                  do_constant_folding=True,  # whether to execute constant folding for optimization
                  input_names = ['input'],   # the model's input names
                  output_names = ['output'], # the model's output names
                  dynamic_axes={'input' : {0 : 'batch_size'},    # variable lenght axes
                                'output' : {0 : 'batch_size'}})

#test the model
import onnx
onnx_model = onnx.load("model.onnx")
onnx.checker.check_model(onnx_model)

import onnxruntime
ort_session = onnxruntime.InferenceSession("model.onnx")
```
 The above throw an error at the very last step:

> RuntimeError: [ONNXRuntimeError] : 10 : INVALID_GRAPH : Load model from model.onnx failed:This is an invalid model. Error in Node: : Node () has input size 4 not in range [min=2, max=2].

**Expected behavior**
It seems to be working find on Windows 10.

labels.name: triaged
labels.description: This issue has been looked at a team member, and triaged and prioritized into an appropriate module

repository.name: pytorch
repository.description: Tensors and Dynamic neural networks in Python with strong GPU acceleration

issue.body:
Hi guys, sorry to disturb you guys. 

I just want to mention that when I saved the model with torch.onnx.export or torch.onnx._export with opset_version=11, then I will "always" get incorrect model whenever the model contains pytorch tensor with "torch.FloatTensor" type. 

You could use this as reference to reproduce: https://discuss.pytorch.org/t/onnx-export-no-bilinear-interpolation-support/42527 (change the input x as torch.rand, and add opset_version=11 to it).

My only working solution is to downgrade the opset_version=10 and it takes me 2.5 days to figure it out (because we want to avoid warnings that will show up on opset_version=10 at first). Hope you guys could take a look at the export function on opset_version 11 so that other people will not stumble on a supposedly-unnecessary bug.

Thank you.
 - PyTorch Version (e.g., 1.0): 1.3.1
 - OS: Windows 10
 - Installed source: pip
 - Python version: 3.6.5
 - CUDA/cuDNN version: 10.0
 - GPU models and configuration: gtx1080
 - Any other relevant information: ONNX 1.6.0
